1. The study (Main Data Source) underwent external peer review prior to this submission to the US LCI database.                                                                               2.  CARBON SEQUESTRATION should be accounted for after the product is built in its LCA model, and should be included depending on the use of end of life fate of that product.  For example, a soy-based resin may retain the sequestered carbon indefinitely, while a soy-based biodiesel releases the sequestered carbon at use phase.  
Biomass carbon contents are as follows: 
CRUDE SOY OIL: 77% C --> 2.823 kg CO2/kg crude soy oil; 
SOY MEAL: 48% C --> 1.76 kg CO2/kg meal; 
REFINED SOY OIL: 80.6% C --> 2.955 kg CO2/kg refined soy oil;
BIODIESEL: 77% C --> 2.823 kg CO2/kg biodiesel.
3 ALLOCATION: THE VALUES IN THE "FLOW INFO" SHEET ARE NOT ALLOCATED, BUT THE DEFAULT ALLOCATION IS ON A PHYSICAL BASIS.  FOR SENSITIVITY, OR DEPENDING ON YOUR GOAL AND SCOPE, ECONOMIC ALLOCATION MAY ALSO BE USED.  FOR EXAMPLE: DECEMBER 2009 ECONOMIC ALLOCATION VALUES WOULD BE: CRUDE OIL: 38%, MEAL: 62%.  LCA PRACTITIONERS ARE ENCOURAGED TO RESEARCH AND USE THE LATEST ECONOMIC DATA BEFORE APPLYING ECONOMIC ALLOCATION FACTORS.
